  "prompt": "What happens if the incumbent president dies on inauguration day of the new president-elect?",
  "response": "If the incumbent president dies on the day of the new president-elect's inauguration, the succession process would depend on the exact timing and circumstances of the death. Here\u2019s how the situation would unfold:\n\n1. **If the incumbent president dies before the new president-elect takes the oath of office**:  \n   - The incumbent president would still be in office at the time of death, as their term officially ends at noon on January 20 (per the 20th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution).  \n   - The Vice President of the incumbent administration would immediately assume the presidency under the Presidential Succession Act until the new president-elect is sworn in.  \n   - Once the new president-elect takes the oath of office at noon, they would officially become president, and the succession process would no longer apply.\n\n2. **If the incumbent president dies after the new president-elect takes the oath of office**:  \n   - The new president-elect would already be the president of the United States, having completed the oath of office.  \n   - There would be no interruption in governance, as the new president would have already assumed power.\n\nIn either case, the timing of the inauguration (which occurs at noon on January 20) is critical to determining who holds the presidency at the moment of the incumbent president's death. The orderly transfer of power is a key feature of the U.S. constitutional system, and the 20th Amendment ensures clarity on the timing of presidential transitions.",
